# HTML5 Elements
## audio

The `AUDIO` tag allows for music and sound to be played within the browser.

||code html||
<audio controls>
  <source src="./music.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
  Sorry, audio is not supported!
</audio>
||code||

<div class="output" >
<audio controls>
  <source src="./music.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
  Sorry, audio is not supported!
</audio>
</div>



[slide]
# HTML5 Elements
## video

The `VIDEO` tag allows for video (with or without sound) to be played within the browser.

||code html||
<video controls >
  <source src="./video.mp4" type="audio/mp4">
  Sorry, video is not supported!
</video>
||code||

<div class="output" >
<video controls muted="true" >
  <source src="./video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  Sorry, video is not supported!
</video>
</div>



[slide]
# HTML5 Elements
## canvas

The `CANVAS` allows you to create drawings in the browser.

||code html||
<canvas id="canvas" >
	Your browser does not support the Canvas tag
</canvas>
<script type="text/javascript" >
	// canvas drawing code...
</script>
||code||

<div class="output" >
<canvas id="canvas" height="100px" >
	Your browser does not support the Canvas tag
</canvas>
<script src="./canvas_example.js" type="text/javascript" ></script>
</div>



[slide]
# HTML5 Elements
## input / `type`

The `INPUT` has several new types that can replace the need for JavaScript powered controls.

||code html||
<input type="date" />
<input type="color" />
<input type="number" />
<input type="range" />
||code||

<div class="output" >
<input type="date" />
<input type="color" />
<input type="number" />
<input type="range" />
</div>



[slide]
# HTML5 Elements
## progress

The `PROGRESS` tag can display a configurable progress bar.

||code html||
<progress value="75" max="100">75%</progress>
||code||

<div class="output" >
<progress value="75" max="100">75%</progress>
</div>




[slide]
# HTML5 Elements
## output

The `OUTPUT` identifies an area that should display a result.

||code html||
<form oninput=
	"out.value=last.value+', '+first.value" >
	<input placeholder="first" name="first" />
	<input placeholder="last" name="last" />
	<br />
	Name: <output name="out">???</output>
</form>
||code||

<div class="output" >
<form oninput="out.value=last.value+', '+first.value" >
	<input placeholder="first" name="first" />
	<input placeholder="last" name="last" />
	<br />
	Name: <output name="out">???</output>
</form>
</div>



